<article>
    <h1>Rail taste of Ja&#xAD;pan</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200927/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-27"><time>2020-09-27</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRAVEL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Set up in 2016, Ja­pan Rail Cafe at Guoco Tower is owned and run by the East Ja­pan Rail­way Com­pany. The cafe re­sem­bles a train sta­tion, com­plete with a rail­way track replica sus­pended from the ceil­ing.</p>
    <p>A sign­board at the en­trance in­di­cates how the cafe is sec­tioned into four “plat­forms” – the com­mu­ni­ca­tor area, rail pass counter, in­door din­ing area and out­door ter­race din­ing area.</p>
    <p>You can usu­ally buy Ja­pan rail passes here, but this ser­vice has been sus­pended due to the pan­demic.</p>
    <p>The cafe has a re­tail cor­ner where you can get sea­sonal food and bev­er­ages from east Ja­pan, such as Ni­igata rice, fu­rikake (rice sea­son­ing) sa­chets from Hokkaido, and Ta­maya Sakura Pasta from Ya­m­a­gata.</p>
    <p>Get a taste of ek­iben (rail­way bento meals). The Ja­pan Rail Cafe Plate ($17) com­prises teriyaki saba fish, tam­ago, veg­eta­bles and three hand­made omusubi – with sal­mon flakes, tem­pura and a monthly spe­cial. Omusubi is a tri­an­gu­lar Ja­panese rice ball wrapped in nori.</p>
    <p>Hafu Hafu Rice ($18) is a hearty dish for those who can­not de­cide be­tween Watashino Curry Rice ($18) – Ja­panese curry with a black pep­per base – and Watashino Hiyashi Rice ($18) – Ja­panese hashed beef stew with a sauce base of tomato puree and red wine.</p>

